      { feature: "Branded academy", values: ["Excellent", "Good", "Good", "Excellent", "Good"] },
      { feature: "Commerce built-in", values: ["Yes — full engine", "Limited", "Limited", "Yes", "Limited"] },
      { feature: "Community features", values: ["Yes — native", "Via integrations", "No", "Limited", "No"] },
      { feature: "AI features", values: ["Yes", "Yes — advanced", "Yes — Aura", "Limited", "Limited"] },
      { feature: "Multi-audience", values: ["Customer-focused", "Yes — all audiences", "Yes — internal + external", "Customer-focused", "Customer + partner"] },
      { feature: "White-label control", values: ["Good", "Good", "Good", "Excellent", "Good"] },
      { feature: "Mobile experience", values: ["Responsive", "App available", "App available", "Custom app builder", "Responsive"] },
      { feature: "Ease of setup", values: ["Easy", "Complex", "Moderate", "Easy", "Moderate"] },
      { feature: "Pricing model", values: ["Transparent tiers", "Custom quote", "Custom quote", "Transparent tiers", "Custom quote"] }
    ]}
  />

  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">How to Choose the Right Platform</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
      The right customer training LMS depends on what you are actually trying to accomplish. Here is a quick decision framework:
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-700 mb-4">
      <li><strong>Choose Thinkific if</strong> you want customer training to also drive revenue, build community, and create ongoing engagement through memberships. It is the strongest option when your academy is both a training tool and a business asset.</li>
      <li><strong>Choose Docebo if</strong> you are an enterprise that needs to train customers alongside employees, partners, and members from a single platform. Its multi-audience architecture and AI capabilities justify the higher price at scale.</li>
      <li><strong>Choose Absorb if</strong> you need enterprise-grade administration, deep analytics, and AI-powered operations for customer training. It is especially strong when you need robust internal and external training in one system.</li>
      <li><strong>Choose LearnWorlds if</strong> white-label control is your top priority. When your branded experience needs to be pixel-perfect and you want a custom mobile app, LearnWorlds gives you the most design flexibility.</li>
      <li><strong>Choose Skilljar if</strong> customer onboarding and adoption are the primary goals and you want a platform purpose-built for that workflow. Its integration with customer success tools makes it natural for CS-led training programs.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-slate-700">
      If you are still unsure, start with the question: <em>Is this primarily about driving product adoption, or is it also a revenue and community play?</em> Adoption-first buyers lean toward purpose-built customer education tools. Revenue and community buyers lean toward learning commerce platforms. Enterprise complexity points to multi-audience enterprise LMS options.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-4 text-slate-700">
      <li>
        <strong>Using an employee LMS for customer training.</strong> Internal LMSs are built for mandatory compliance training, not voluntary customer education. They typically lack external learner management, branding controls, and the low-friction experience customers expect. You will fight the tool instead of serving your learners.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Ignoring the branded experience.</strong> Your customers judge your company partly by the training experience you deliver. A generic or vendor-branded portal undermines the professionalism you have built everywhere else. Invest in branding from day one.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Treating customer training as a one-time onboarding event.</strong> The most effective customer education programs are ongoing. Platforms that support community, memberships, and continuous content delivery create significantly more value than onboarding-only setups.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Not connecting training to business outcomes.</strong> Completion rates are vanity metrics. Measure what matters: churn rate changes, time-to-value, support ticket reduction, product adoption depth, and expansion revenue. If your LMS cannot help you track these, it is missing the point.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <LeadFormModal
